<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>Chen's blog (Posts about cpanm)</title><link>http://blog.binchen.org/</link><description></description><atom:link href="http://blog.binchen.org/categories/cpanm.xml" type="application/rss+xml" rel="self"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 12 Apr 2020 05:44:24 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Install perl module through source package on cygwin by using cpanm</title><link>http://blog.binchen.org/posts/install-perl-module-through-source-package-on-cygwin-by-using-cpanm.html</link><dc:creator>Chen Bin</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;
I failed to install package "Template" by running `cpanm Template'.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
It's because the binary package requires gcc4 while on my cygwin only gcc3 available.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
So I install it from source package (with some hack, of course),
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="org-src-container"&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class="lang-sh"&gt;cpanm --look Template # Download and unpack the distribution and then open the directory with your shellI
cpanm . #install from local directory
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
Updated: The simpler solution is to install gcc4 at cygwin.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>cpan</category><category>cpanm</category><category>en</category><category>install</category><category>module</category><category>perl</category><guid>http://blog.binchen.org/posts/install-perl-module-through-source-package-on-cygwin-by-using-cpanm.html</guid><pubDate>Tue, 17 Jul 2012 23:22:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>